<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Confidence Intervals</h1>=20


<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ci4p=
m2.svg" alt=3D"confidence interval 4 plus or minus 2" height=3D"109" width=
=3D"292"><br>
An interval of <b>4 plus or minus 2</b></p>=20
<p>A Confidence Interval is a <b>range of values</b>  we are fairly sure ou=
r <b>true value</b> lies in.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p style=3D"float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;"><img src=3D"https://www.ma=
thsisfun.com/data/images/men.jpg" alt=3D"men running" height=3D"155" width=
=3D"240"></p>=20

	<h3>Example: Average Height</h3>=20

	<p>We measure the heights of <b>40</b> randomly chosen men, and get a <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/mean.html">mean</a> height of <b>175cm</b=
>,</p>=20
	<p>We also know the  <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-d=
eviation.html">standard deviation</a> of men's heights is <b>20cm</b>.</p>=
=20
	<p>The <b>95% Confidence Interval</b> (we  show how to calculate it later)=
 is:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ci1=
75pm.svg" alt=3D"confidence interval 175 plus minus 6.2" height=3D"93" widt=
h=3D"206"></p>=20
	<p>The "<b>=C2=B1</b>" means "plus or minus", so <b>175cm =C2=B1 6,2cm</b>=
 means</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>175cm =E2=88=92 6,2cm =3D 168,8cm <b>to&nbsp;</b></li>=20
		<li>175cm + 6,2cm =3D 181,2cm</li>
	</ul>=20
	<p>And our result says the <b>true mean</b>  of ALL men (if we could measu=
re all their heights) is likely to be between 168,8cm and 181,2cm</p>=20
	<p><i>But it might not be!</i></p>=20
	<p>The "95%" says that 95% of  experiments like we just did will include t=
he true mean, but <b>5% won't</b>.</p>=20
	<p>So there is a 1-in-20 chance (5%) that our Confidence Interval does NOT=
 include the true mean.</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Calculating the Confidence Interval</h2>=20

<p><b>Step 1</b>: start with</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>the number of observations <b>n</b></li>=20
	<li>the mean <b><span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid black;">X</span></b><=
/li>=20
	<li>and the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-deviation.=
html">standard deviation</a> <b>s</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p>Note: we should  use  the  standard deviation of the entire <b>populatio=
n</b>, but in many cases we won't know it.</p>=20
<p>We can  use  the standard deviation for the <b>sample</b> if we have eno=
ugh observations (at least n=3D30, hopefully more).</p>=20
</div>
<p>Using our  example:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>number of observations <b>n =3D 40</b></li>=20
	<li>mean <b><span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid black;">X</span> =3D 175<=
/b></li>=20
	<li>standard deviation <b>s =3D 20</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
<p><b>Step 2</b>: decide what Confidence Interval we want (95% or 99% are c=
ommon choices). Then find the "Z" value for that Confidence Interval here:<=
/p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>Confidence<br>
Interval</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>Z</b></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">80%</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">1,282</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">85%</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">1,440</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">90%</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">1,645</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">95%</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">1,960</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">99%</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">2,576</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">99,5%</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">2,807</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">99,9%</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">3,291</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p>For 95% the Z value is <b>1,960</b></p>=20
<p><b>Step 3</b>: use that Z value in this formula for the Confidence Inter=
val:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger"><span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid black;">X</=
span>&nbsp; =C2=B1  &nbsp;Z<span class=3D"intbl"><em>s</em><strong>=E2=88=
=9An</strong></span></p>=20
<p>Where:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid black;"><b>X</b></span> is the me=
an</li>=20
	<li><b>Z</b> is the chosen Z-value from the table above</li>=20
	<li><b>s</b> is the standard deviation</li>=20
	<li><b>n</b> is the number of observations</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>And we have:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">175 =C2=B1 1,960 =C3=97 <span class=3D"intbl"><e=
m>20</em><strong>=E2=88=9A40</strong></span></p>=20
<p>Which is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger"><b>175cm =C2=B1 6,20cm</b></p>=20
<p>In other words: from 168,8cm to 181,2cm</p>=20
<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>The value after the =C2=B1 is called the <b>margin of error</b></p>=20
<p>The margin of error in our example is 6,20cm</p>=20
</div>
<p style=3D"float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;"><a href=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/data/confidence-interval-calculator.html"><img src=3D"https://ww=
w.mathsisfun.com/data/images/conf-interval-calc.gif" alt=3D"confidence inte=
rval calculator" height=3D"144" width=3D"150"></a></p>=20


<h2>Calculator</h2>=20

<p>We have a <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/confidence-interval=
-calculator.html">Confidence Interval Calculator</a> to make life easier fo=
r you.</p>=20
<!-- <div style=3D"clear:both"></div> -->


<h2>Simulator</h2>=20

<p>We also have a very interesting <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/da=
ta/normal-distribution-simulator.html">Normal Distribution Simulator</a>. w=
here we can start with some theoretical "true" mean and standard deviation,=
 and then take random samples.</p>=20
<p>It helps us to understand how random samples can sometimes be very good =
or bad at representing the underlying true values.</p>=20


<h2>Another Example</h2>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p style=3D"float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;"><img src=3D"https://www.ma=
thsisfun.com/data/images/apple-tree.jpg" alt=3D"apple tree" height=3D"134" =
width=3D"186"></p>=20

	<h3>Example: Apple Orchard</h3>=20

	<p>Are the apples big enough?</p>=20
	<p>There are hundreds of apples on the trees, so you randomly choose just =
<b>46</b> apples and get:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>a Mean of <b>86</b></li>=20
		<li>a Standard Deviation of <b>6,2</b></li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>So let's  calculate:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger"><span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid black;">X<=
/span>&nbsp; =C2=B1  &nbsp;Z<span class=3D"intbl"><em>s</em><strong>=E2=88=
=9An</strong></span></p>=20
	<p>We know:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li><span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid black;"><b>X</b></span> is the m=
ean =3D 86</li>=20
		<li><b>Z</b> is the Z-value =3D 1,960 (from the table above for 95%)</li>=
=20
		<li><b>s</b> is the standard deviation =3D 6,2</li>=20
		<li><b>n</b> is the number of observations  =3D 46</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">86 =C2=B1 1,960 =C3=97 <span class=3D"intbl"><e=
m>6,2</em><strong>=E2=88=9A46</strong></span>  =3D <b>86 =C2=B1 1,79</b></p=
>=20
	<p>So the true mean (of all the hundreds of apples) is <b>likely</b> to be=
 between 84,21 and 87,79</p>=20

	<h3>True Mean</h3>=20

	<p>Now imagine we get to pick ALL  the apples  straight away, and get them=
  ALL measured by the packing machine&nbsp;(this is a luxury not normally f=
ound in statistics!)</p>=20
	<p>And the <b>true mean</b> turns out to be<b> 84,9</b></p>=20
	<p>Let's lay all the apples on the ground from smallest to largest:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ci1=
.svg" alt=3D"confidence interval 86 plus minus 1.79" height=3D"205" width=
=3D"256"><br>
Each apple is a green dot,<br>
our  observations are marked&nbsp; blue</p>=20
	<p>Our result was not exact ... it is random after all&nbsp;... but  the t=
rue mean is inside our confidence interval of 86 =C2=B1 1,79 (in other word=
s 84,21 to 87,79)</p>=20
	<p>Now the true mean<b> might not</b> be  inside the confidence interval, =
but in <b>95% of the cases it will be!</b></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large">95% of all "95% Confidence Intervals" will inclu=
de the true mean.</p>=20
	<p>Maybe we had this sample, with   a mean of  83,5:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ci3=
.svg" alt=3D"confidence interval 83.5 plus minus 1.25" height=3D"212" width=
=3D"256"><br>
Each&nbsp;apple is a green dot,<br>
our observations  are marked purple</p>=20
	<p>That <b>does not&nbsp;include the true mean.</b> That can happen about =
5% of the time for a 95% confidence interval.</p>=20
	<p>So how do we know if our sample is one of the "lucky" 95% or the unluck=
y 5%? Unless we get to measure the whole population like above we simply <b=
>don't know</b>.</p>=20
	<p>This is the risk in <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/sampling=
.html">sampling</a>, we might  have a "bad" sample.</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Example in Research</h2>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Here is   Confidence Interval used in actual research on   <b>extra exe=
rcise for older people</b>:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ci-=
extract2.gif" alt=3D"confidence interval extract" style=3D"border: 1px soli=
d blue;" height=3D"106" width=3D"549"></p>=20
	<p>What is it saying? Looking at the   "Male" line we see:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>1.226 Men  (47,6% of all people)</li>=20
		<li>had a "HR" (see below)  with a <b>mean of 0,92</b>,</li>=20
		<li>and a <b>95% Confidence Interval&nbsp;(95% CI) of 0,88 to 0,97</b> (w=
hich is also 0,92=C2=B10,05)</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>"HR" is a measure of health benefit (lower is better), so it says that =
the <b>true benefit of exercise</b> for the  wider population of men has a =
<b>95% chance</b> of being between 0,88 and 0,97</p>=20
	<p><i>* Note for the curious: "HR"  is used a lot in health  research and =
means "Hazard Ratio" where lower is better. So an HR of 0,92 means the subj=
ects were better off, and a 1,03 means slightly worse off.</i></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Standard Normal Distribution</h2>=20

<p>It is all based on the idea of the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com=
/data/standard-normal-distribution-table.html">Standard Normal Distribution=
</a>, where the <span class=3D"large">Z</span> value is the "Z-score"</p>=
=20
<p>For example the <span class=3D"large">Z</span> for 95% is 1,960, and her=
e we see the range from -1,96 to +1,96 includes 95% of all values:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ci95=
.svg" alt=3D"confidence interval 95%" height=3D"142" width=3D"295"><br>
From -1,96 to +1,96 standard deviations is 95%</p>=20
<p>Applying that to our sample looks like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/ci4.=
svg" alt=3D"confidence interval 86 plus minus 1.79 bell" height=3D"212" wid=
th=3D"256"><br>
Also from -1,96 to +1,96 standard deviations,  so  includes  95%</p>=20


<h2>Conclusion</h2>=20

<p>The Confidence Interval&nbsp;is based on Mean and Standard Deviation. It=
s formula is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large"><span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid black;">X</s=
pan>&nbsp; =C2=B1  &nbsp;Z<span class=3D"intbl"><em>s</em><strong>=E2=88=9A=
n</strong></span></p>=20
<p>Where:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><span style=3D"border-top: 1px solid black;"><b>X</b></span> is the me=
an</li>=20
	<li><b>Z</b> is the Z-value from the table below</li>=20
	<li><b>s</b> is the standard deviation</li>=20
	<li><b>n</b> is the number of observations</li>=20
</ul>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

